node.text:
On this episode of AD Visits, sartorial sensation Eva Chen (@evachen212) invites us inside her Connecticut home designed by local firm @hendrickschurchill. See her many reading nooks, her @instagram-worthy kitchen, and more. Cover photo by @chrismottalini; styled by Dorcia Kelly.

Visit our link in bio to read more about her home.

node.text: We're back with another episode of AD Visits, and today, we're taking you to Hudson Yards to see the home of fashion designer @brian_atwood and husband @drjakedeutsch. With photography on every wall and incredible city views 64 stories above Manhattan, explore their high-rise artistic aerie. Cover photo by @twilliamsphoto.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Architectural Digest on August 23, 2021. May be an image of table and indoor.

node.text:
“I couldn’t be any happier with the way this house lives and looks," says homeowner David Ren of his Hudson Valley Victorian home. Here, a @workstead pendant hangs above a custom @nathanlindbergdesign dining table and Gino Russo chairs.

Explore every space at our bio link. Photo by @matthewwilliamson; design by @workstead; styling by @mieketenhave; words by David Sokol.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Architectural Digest on August 23, 2021. May be an image of living room.

node.text:
For both @davidtotah's gallery and his East Village home, intuition guides decision making. Totah seeks out slow-read art, or art made in a meditative state, for the walls of his apartment. This wall includes works by, from right to left: @artistgeorgecondo, @david.austen, Aleksandar Duravcevic, Bruce Connor, @rayjohnsonestate, Hassan Khan, @marsha_cottrell, Wallace Berman, Roger Ackling, and @sarah.l.peters. 

Take a tour at our bio link. Photo by @jeffholt; words by @christianelemieux.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Architectural Digest on August 23, 2021. May be an image of furniture and living room.

node.text:
It’s been over a decade since interior designer @thomfilicia purchased and renovated his own weekend home in New York’s Finger Lakes region. Filicia might as well be the Skaneateles Lake’s mayor, given the way he raves about its appeal. “It’s a really beautiful town because it’s right on the water,” he says. "It’s just a really special place.” So special that his very close friends—a family of five—had decided to build their main residence on a swathe of land on the west side of the same lake.

See the family retreat at our bio link. Photo by Amy Lamb; design by @thomfilicia; words by @arielfoxman.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Architectural Digest on August 22, 2021. May be an image of indoor.

node.text:
“To feel tranquility in a space, everything needs to be in order,” says Ashton Kutcher (@aplusk) of the home he shares with Mila Kunis. “If the world around you isn’t in order, it’s hard to get your brain in order. When we’re in our home, the world just makes sense.” In the kitchen, @bomma_cz pendants illuminate the @sebastiancoxltd Kitchen by @devolkitchens.

Explore their stunning modern farmhouse at our bio link. Photo by @douglasfriedman; styling by @michaelreynoldsnyc; design by @charlesandcostudio; architecture by @backengillamarchitects; words by @mayer.rus.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Architectural Digest on August 22, 2021. May be an image of table, indoor and text that says '거'.

node.text:
Exposed wooden beams create a sense of geometry in model @taylor_hill's dining room, which features a round wood table large enough to fit her visiting family. Blue is a color that reoccurs throughout the room, from the framed blueprints of the home to the mismatched chairs (painted by Hill’s mother) to the Blue Willow china displayed in the corner cabinets. “All of the dishware is my Grandma Gloria’s,” Hill explains. “My mom has hung on to all of her things.”

See more from her home at our bio link. Photo by @alyssarosenheck; styled by @alyssarosenheck; words by @libbycallaway1970.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Architectural Digest on August 22, 2021. May be an image of furniture, chandelier and indoor.

node.text:
“Design in general is not one of our strengths, so it was key to work with a team that we trusted and [that we] could empower to manage every detail from start to finish,” says one of the owners of this home on Lake Austin. “We just knew that we wanted the space to feel connect[ed to] the lake and [to] the outdoors in general.”

Step inside at our bio link. Photo by @douglasfriedman; design by @ryanstreetarchitects and @studioseiders; words by @whatpaolasees.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Architectural Digest on August 21, 2021. May be an image of indoor.

node.text:
Since @evachen212's family moved into the home in the summer of 2020, the slog of urban parenting has given way to long, happy country days, as children Ren and Tao splash around the pond and survey the grounds, looking for newts, dragonflies, geese, turtles, and bunnies. “Losing structure has been the greatest gift,” says Chen. “I never thought I’d be that person in gardening clogs.”

Tour her Connecticut home at our bio link. Photo by @chrismottalini; produced by @janekeltnerdev; styled by @kellemiles; design by @hendrickschurchill; words by @samuelcochran.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Architectural Digest on August 21, 2021. May be an image of furniture and outdoors.

node.text:
“We replaced all of the doors and windows and made them floor-to-ceiling,” says architect and designer @eddiemaestri of the 14-foot-tall sliding doors at the Dallas home he shares with husband Adam. “And we changed out the canvas awning to a black-and-white stripe, a recurring theme in the house.” The couple replaced all of the existing concrete pool decking with artificial turf, and covered the porch and terrace in Pascal tiles by @conceptsurfaces.

Visit our bio link to explore the whole home. Photo by @nathanschroderphoto; styled by @jennyoconnorstudio; design by @maestristudio; words by @whatpaolasees.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Architectural Digest on August 21, 2021. May be an image of table and living room.

node.text:
Subtle gestures throughout this L.A. home were calculated to lend intimacy and texture to specific rooms without overshadowing the integrity of the architecture. Designers @nateberkus and @jeremiahbrent cloaked the four walls of the dining room in suede curtains, for instance, and sheathed a powder room in a coat of paint resembling mottled Venetian plaster.

Step inside at our bio link. Photo by @trevortondro; styling by @colinking; design by @nateberkus and @jeremiahbrent; architecture by @mccleandesign; words by @mayer.rus.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Architectural Digest on August 20, 2021. May be an image of furniture and bedroom.

node.text:
“It’s a little jewel box, and we were able to choose really special finishes that make it sparkle,” says @biscuithome founder and hospitality entrepreneur Bailey McCarthy (@baileyquin) about her Chicago pied-à-terre. “I wanted it to feel like the best hotel room you could imagine. It’s a city pad, so it had to be unfussy and a place from which you could easily come and go.”

See the transformed home at our bio link. Photo by @aimeemazzenga; styling by @cate.ragan.styling and @darwin.fitz.design; design by @baileyquin; words by @allisonpduncan.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Architectural Digest on August 20, 2021. May be an image of kitchen.

node.text:
Painting kitchen cabinets is a straightforward DIY task that makes a major impact. Think about how your newly painted doors and drawers will highlight a beloved backsplash or enhance some dated fronts. If you’re looking to upgrade your kitchen, it’s time to learn how to paint kitchen cabinets. It’s relatively cheap, totally transformative, and will make you feel incredibly proud. If you’re particularly motivated, it could even be a doable weekend DIY project.

Get expert tips at our bio link. Photo by @francoishalard; words by @kenziwilbur and @zoesessums.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Architectural Digest on August 20, 2021. May be an image of sofa and living room.

node.text:
“Art is a portal to another dimension,” @davidtotah, curator and founder of Totah, a New York gallery on the Lower East Side of Manhattan, says. As a curator, he looks for art that “takes one to another place.” Fittingly, Totah’s East Village apartment brims with work by influential artists such as @kennyscharf and Alighiero Boetti.

Take a tour at our bio link. Photo by @jeffholt; words by @christianelemieux.
